This transition will all happen over time forcing a reinvestment in what provides energy, reliability, and (yes) energy security today. It will continue to be messy & muddled, but can be done mindful of many of the points @JasonBordoff & @OSullivanMeghan have pointed to here.

Electrification will serve as a natural hedge against over exposure to any single fuel or resource because it is generated in so many different ways and is localized. That becomes the “energy security” function while manufacturing & mineral/fuel sourcing happens across the globe.

My take: Interconnected supply chains across world markets will become more important. This runs counter to the current push across the globe to onshore. Resolving that tension will be key to how fast and how affordable the clean energy future happens.

The Local Plan sets out how the Council can meet the government's targets to 2040 and makes allocations to deliver new housing and employment. Last year the government increased number of homes that must be planned for in Bedford Borough by 40% to 1,355 a year, ever year to 2040.

The policies include contributing to more walkable and cycle-able neighbourhoods, incorporating renewable and low carbon energy infrastructure, and retrofitting existing buildings with measures to reduce energy consumption.
